english:
  title: Explanation of the Courtesy Name for the Grand Prince of Hyogyeong
  author: Byeon Gyeyang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Grand Prince of Hyogyeong spoke to Gyeyang, saying: "A name must have a courtesy name—this is the ancient custom. My name is 'Po,' meaning to mend. I ask that you bestow upon me a courtesy name, and compose an explanation for it. I wish to read it and thereby admonish myself." Gyeyang dared not refuse.

    I have long observed the Commentary on the Changes, which states: "One who excels at mending flaws." And in the Greater Odes of the Poetry Classic, it is written: "When the lord's robes lack adornment, only Zhong Shanfu mended them." For one must first mend one's own flaws before one can mend the lord's shortcomings—this order cannot be reversed. Therefore, I propose the courtesy name "Shangshu"—Good Uncle.

    For goodness is the original nature given by Heaven, inherent in all people alike, neither diminished by external circumstance nor lost to time. Whether one is Yao or Shun, or a humble commoner, there is no difference in this regard. Yet the endowment of temperament binds us from within, and material desires cloud us from without. Thus our conduct inevitably suffers some flaw or misstep—a weakness none can escape. Confucius lamented this deeply and inscribed it in the Changes, his concern for future generations boundless.

    Alas, who among mortals is without fault? When we use goodness to mend it, we succeed. Thus is Tang's virtue praised: "He repented of errors without reluctance." The Duke of Zhou too was not free from faults. Confucius wished that people would recognize their own transgressions, and he himself said, "Should one master the Changes, one might avoid grave mistakes." If sages themselves are thus, how much more the rest of us?

    Beginning with goodness mending our flaws, we ultimately arrive at a state beyond fault. Then does the robe of office need no mending, the mandate of Heaven requires no correction—whatever path one takes, all is proper; wherever one goes, all is reached. Thus one comes to make all under Heaven good, and the mysterious workings become one with Heaven and Earth above and below.

    I observe that the Grand Prince, graced with gentle dignity and brilliant cultivation, practices filial piety, brotherly respect, loyalty, and trustworthiness with steadfast commitment. Though he dwells in the highest station and pursues learning without weariness, he humbles himself in self-cultivation, showing not the slightest trace of arrogance or self-regard. How virtuous! Yet he remains unsatisfied with himself and seeks counsel from me to further admonish himself. The ancients spoke truly: "The dignified who practice humility shine all the brighter," and "The superior learns without shame." Surely they spoke of the Grand Prince.

    Not yet thirty, the Grand Prince already embodies such excellence of learning and character—how can one measure what his future accomplishments shall be? Surely he merits the affection of the Former Majesties and the brotherhood of His Majesty, serving as exemplar to the royal kindred, nurturing the virtue of his superiors, preserving wealth and honor eternal, and sharing in the kingdom's glory without end. Of this there is no doubt. Is this not beautiful?

    Regarding the sages' commentary on the Changes, though I have long savored it, I have not fathomed its depths—how dare I presume to elaborate its meaning? Yet the impulse to aid others in goodness springs from Heaven's inborn righteousness, and thus I cannot contain my sense of gratitude at the Grand Prince's inquiry. I humbly present this courtesy name with its explanation, joining it with verse:

    When mortals harbor flaw,
    Mend it well with good—
    Once the flaw is mended,
    Set the lord's course straight.
    Body and function spring from one source;
    Before and after have their proper order.
    Great deeds and glory,
    With sages all converge.
    Heaven sends down blessing and fortune—
    These shall descend and endure.

    Virtuous Grand Prince!
    Let goodness be your teacher,
    Let loyalty and filial love
    Dwell constant in your heart.
    In study, diligence—
    Each day, unwavering zeal.
    The heart's affection
    Springs from inborn nature.
    Though love cannot be withheld,
    I pledge it here in verse.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Po (補) means "to mend" or "to repair," referring to correcting flaws or supplying what is lacking.
  - key: ''
    value: Zhong Shanfu (仲山甫) was a celebrated minister of the Zhou dynasty, known for his exemplary service in assisting the ruler.
  - key: ''
    value: The "Greater Odes" (大雅) reference alludes to the poem about the Duke of Zhou and his role in supporting the throne.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase "body and function spring from one source" (體用一源) draws from Neo-Confucian philosophy regarding the unity of principle and its manifestation.
  - key: ''
    value: The Grand Prince of Hyogyeong was a historical figure of the Joseon dynasty, and this piece was composed as an auspicious document celebrating his character.
